===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

Originally written as {{m|zh|畮|tr=-}}, a {{Han compound|ls=psc|c1=s|田|t1=field|c2=p|每|nocap=1}}. The phonetic component {{m|zh|每|tr=-}} was later replaced with {{m|zh|又|tr=-}}, now written as the new phonetic component {{och-l|久}}. The component {{m|zh|十|tr=-}} was added above {{m|zh|田|tr=-}} in the Warring States period and was later corrupted into {{m|zh|亠|tr=-}} in clerical script.

===Etymology===
Possibly {{der|zh|sit}}. Compare {{cog|bo|རྨོ}}, {{m|bo|རྨོས||to plow}}, {{m|bo|རྨོད||t=plowing}}, {{m|bo|རྨོན་པ||plow-ox}}, {{cog|mjw|tr=-mò|t=classifier for strips of fields}} ({{zh-ref|Bodman, 1980}}; {{zh-ref|Baxter, 1992}}; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

{{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} also suggests a connection to an {{der|zh|aav}} root, whence {{cog|okz|cval||to enter; to penetrate; (of animals) to copulate}}, {{cog|kjg|tr=cmɔɔl|t=to plant (rice) with a digging stick}}, {{m|kjg|tr=crmɔɔl|t=digging stick}} (cf. {{zh-ref|Ferlus, 1987}}). The semantic development would be “digging stick” > “plowing” > “mu”. He also connects this to {{och-l|牡|male animal}}; see there for more.

